{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9e1ba9a4-1e34-41bb-a2de-bd7e4a9f8c5e","content":"## What Changed\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, overload resolution now prefers **`MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)`** over `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)` for arrays, because arrays are implicitly convertible to `ReadOnlySpan<T>` and that overload is considered a more specific match.\n\n`ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct**, which **cannot appear in expression trees**. So the expression tree either fails to compile or produces a tree that blows up at runtime when interpreted/compiled.\n\n## Fix\n\nForce the compiler to resolve to `Enumerable.Contains` by either casting or calling it explicitly:\n\n**Option A — cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>`:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\n**Option B — call `Enumerable.Contains` as a static method:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\nBoth bypass the Span-based overload and keep the expression tree valid.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"37dab7a0-1a80-4c87-b5dc-379ed35aedd4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 related to LINQ expression trees and the `.Contains()` method on arrays.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 that would cause this.\n\nIn .NET 10, there's a breaking change related to how the C# compiler resolves extension methods. In C# 14 (which ships with .NET 10), the compiler introduces **extension members** (a new language feature), and more importantly, there's a change in how `System.Linq.Enumerable.Contains` is resolved for arrays.\n\nActually, let me think more carefully. The issue is likely related to the fact that in .NET 10, `System.Array` or arrays now implement some new interfaces or there are new overloads that change method resolution.\n \nThe real problem is that the compiler now prefers `System.MemoryExtensions.Contains` for `Span<T>` and `ReadOnlySpan<T>` over the LINQ `Enumerable.Contains` method. Since `Span<T>` is a ref struct that can't be used in expression trees, this preference causes the runtime failure when the compiler tries to compile the expression tree with the incompatible overload. I'm realizing the real issue: in C# 14 / .NET 10, `array.Contains(num)` now resolves to `System.MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<int>, int)` instead of the LINQ version, because arrays implicitly convert to `ReadOnlySpan<T>`. Since expression trees can't contain ref struct operations, this causes a runtime error when the expression tree is evaluated. I think the real issue is that in C# 14, `array.Contains(num)` inside an expression tree gets resolved to `MemoryExtensions.Contains` with a `ReadOnlySpan<T>` parameter, but expression trees can't handle ref struct types—so this either fails at compile time with an error about ref structs, or possibly at runtime if the expression somehow gets constructed despite that incompatibility. which can't be represented properly in the expression tree system. The solution is to explicitly route to `Enumerable.Contains` either by calling it directly or casting the array to `IEnumerable<int>` first. I'm confident the issue stems from C# 14's improved overload resolution causing `array.Contains(x)` to bind to `MemoryExtensions.Contains` instead of `Enumerable.Contains`, and since expression trees don't support ref structs, this breaks at runtime.","outputTokens":1920,"requestId":"B00E:1ED665:A5E3A0:BF9007:69F2A82B"},"id":"603458fc-7715-4182-9144-2be7456bf925","timestamp":"2026-04-30T00:54:42.594Z","parentId":"e31f7a01-e55e-4f3f-85b0-d69995841e0e"}
